headline: Nvidia chip shift to smartphone-style memory to double server-memory prices by end-2026 - Counterpoint

In the past two months, electronics supply chains around the world have been hit by a shortage ‌of legacy memory chips as manufacturers turned their focus to high-end memory chips suited to semiconductors designed for AI applications.  Nvidia recently decided to reduce AI server power costs by ⁠changing the kind of memory chip ‌it uses to LPDDR, a type of low-power memory chip normally found in phones and tablets, from DDR5, which are typically ‍used in servers.

headline: AI Weekly: Mega deals and Molière-inspired plays
summary:
STORY: From multi-billion dollar deals, to plays written with AI -- this is AI Weekly. -- 

:: AI Weekly

Microsoft and Nvidia have made a mega deal with Claude-maker Anthropic, featuring tens of billions of dollars of spending.

It includes a $30 billion commitment by the AI company to Microsoft's cloud services, Azure.

 And both Nvidia and Microsoft committing up to $10 billion and $5 billion in Anthropic, respectively. 

The agreement brings together major players in the AI industry, with Claude being a major rival to ChatGPT.

Elon Musk’s artificial-intelligence startup xAI is in advanced talks to raise $15 billion in new equity - at a valuation of $230 billion.

That's according to the Wall Street Journal. 

The new valuation would more than double the amount disclosed in March.

The startup has been rapidly scaling its data-center footprint to train more advanced models, as it tries to close the gap with OpenAI’s ChatGPT and Anthropic’s Claude. 

Bank of America is planning to spend $4 billion more in new technology, including AI, to boost bankers' productivity and drive revenue growth.

The bank's chief technology officer said its 18,000 developers have used AI agents for the past year, with significant gains in productivity.

The second-biggest U.S. lender sends AI-generated market information to its financial advisers, combined with data on clients' portfolios, so that bankers can better tailor their investment advice.

Nvidia's move to use smartphone-style memory chips in its AI servers could cause server-memory prices to double by late 2026.

That's according to a report published Wednesday by Counterpoint Research.

Electronics supply chains worldwide have been hit by a shortage of legacy memory chips in the last two months.

Manufacturers have turned their focus to high-end memory chips suited to semiconductors.

Counterpoint says Nvidia's decision to reduce AI server power costs, by changing the kind of memory chip it uses, could create sudden demand that the industry is not prepared for.

:: Sorbonne Universite / Theatre Moliere Sorbonne

And, scholars have teamed up with an AI collective in Paris to create a new play written in the style of the famous 17th-century playwright Moliere.

Over the last three years, the team has trained the French-developed Mistral AI on Moliere's works, personal library texts, and historical documents to replicate his language and humor.

A production called "The Astrologer or the False Omens" is set to debut at the Chateau de Versailles in May 2026.

headline: Nvidia earnings clear lofty hurdle set by analysts amid fears about an AI bubble
summary: Nvidia’s sales of the computing chips powering the artificial intelligence craze surged beyond the lofty bar set by stock market analysts in a performance that may ease recent jitters about a Big Tech boom turning into a bust that topples the world’s most valuable company.  The results announced late Wednesday provided a pulse check on the frenzied spending on AI technology that has been fueling both the stock market and much of the overall economy since OpenAI released its ChatGPT three years ago.  Nvidia has been by far the biggest beneficiary of the run-up because its processors have become indispensable for building the AI factories that are needed to enable what’s supposed to be the most dramatic shift in technology since Apple released the iPhone in 2007.

headline: Nvidia's CFO Pushes Back on GPU Accounting Questions
summary: Nvidia CFO Colette Kress pushed back on recent questions around the useful life of AI chips and the impact on depreciation costs.  “The long, useful life of Nvidia’s CUDA GPUs is a significant TCO [total cost of ownership] advantage over [rival] accelerators,” she said on the earnings call. headline: U.S. Approves Deal to Sell AI Chips to Middle East
summary: The Commerce Department approved the sale of up to 70,000 advanced artificial-intelligence chips to two companies based in the United Arab Emirates and Saudi Arabia, a big win for the Middle East nations as they seek to catch up in the AI race.  The approvals are a reversal from earlier this year, when some administration officials rejected the idea of exporting directly to the state-backed companies over security concerns. headline: Wall Street ends rocky session higher ahead of Nvidia earnings
summary:
STORY: U.S. stocks ended a choppy session higher on Wednesday, with the Dow ticking up marginally, the S&P 500 adding more than a third of a percent and the tech-heavy Nasdaq gaining over half a percent.

Investors were laser-focused on earnings from Nvidia, which reported quarterly results after the market close.

Shares of the AI chip leader, which ended almost 3% higher, climbed further in extended trading after the company forecast fourth-quarter revenue above Wall Street estimates.

Brian Mulberry, client portfolio manager at Zacks Investment Management, says the company's strong results, and ensuing stock move, could help the S&P 500 close out the week on a high note.

“So whatever happens to this particular stock (Nvidia), it has an outsized impact on the broader index just because of its weight, you know, the market cap being over 5 trillion dollars. But as I look at the beta (a measure of a stock's volatility, or risk, relative to the overall market) here recently, it's a 2.1, which means, again, you have the largest constituent by market cap moving at twice the amount of the market. So whatever happens, good or bad, it's going to have an outsized impact on what the trading looks like for the next couple of days.”

Shares of fellow chipmaker Broadcom and chip equipment maker Applied Materials each closed more than 4% higher.

Among the day's decliners, Target shares slipped nearly 3% after the retailer reported a bigger-than-expected drop in quarterly sales.

Investors now turn their attention to Thursday's release of the September jobs report following the record-long U.S. government shutdown.

headline: Nvidia (NASDAQ:NVDA) Surprises With Q3 Sales But Inventory Levels Increase
summary: Leading designer of graphics chips Nvidia (NASDAQ:NVDA) reported Q3 CY2025 results topping the market’s revenue expectations, with sales up 62.5% year on year to $57.01 billion. On top of that, next quarter’s revenue guidance ($65 billion at the midpoint) was surprisingly good and 4.2% above what analysts were expecting. Its non-GAAP profit of $1.30 per share was 3.8% above analysts’ consensus estimates.

headline: Nvidia's strong forecast calms AI bubble jitters, for now
summary: (Reuters) -Nvidia CEO Jensen Huang on Wednesday shrugged off concerns about an AI bubble as the company surprised Wall Street with accelerating growth after several quarters of slowing sales.  Global ​markets have looked to the chip designer to determine whether investing billions of dollars in AI infrastructure expansion has resulted in an AI bubble.  "There's been a lot of talk about an AI bubble.‌ From our vantage point, we see something very different," CEO Jensen Huang said on a call with analysts, where he touted how much cloud companies wanted Nvidia chips.
